[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Welcome. You\'re [music] just in time for casting. &gt;&gt; I\'m Amber and I\'m reading for the part of Jessica. &gt;&gt; I\'m Bob. I\'m reading for the part of Cliff. &gt;&gt; I\'m Tracy and I\'m reading for the part of Jessica.'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; I\'m Daryl. Sorry, I\'m Kevin. I don\'t know why. Sorry, I\'m a little nervous. Okay. &gt;&gt; I\'m Cindy and I\'m reading for the part of Jessica. &gt;&gt; So, it\'s a problem or a challenge that every AI filmmaker is going to reach at some point if they\'re serious. You got a'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'story and you need characters that stay consistent throughout every shot of every scene and not just how they look and even how they sound. But, if you\'re really serious, the nuances of their performance. And if you happen to be'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dealing with real people or actors who have a specific acting style, you\'re going to want to transfer that style into their performance. And you can\'t do that with just an image and an audio. So, how do you create these characters that you can actually control? One for'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'every emotional moment your story needs. So, that when you\'re generating a scene, you\'re using the exact right reference for that moment. Now, what you just watched were pieces'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the audition process for an upcoming AI film. You saw the auditions for Cliff and Jessica, but there\'s one more character we need to add to the mix and we\'re going to create that character right here from scratch so you can see one of many ways that these consistent'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'characters can be created. Now, from the OpenArt page, we\'re going to click character because that\'s what we\'re creating. And in this case, we\'re going to start with describing your character. This allows you to choose from several models and different styles'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and prompt exactly the character you\'d like to see. So, I put a fairly detailed prompt that Claude helped me write to get all the details of this character and the various nuances to make sure that his look even had something of an emotional expression. Once you type in'

[01:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your prompt, you can choose how many samples you\'d like to see and then click generate. Now, if you like any of these results, you can just click on set as character and your character will be set. In my case, I was looking for something a little edgier than those models could'

[01:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'give me. So, I went into the image generation section of the site, chose the GPT image 2 model, and then I got this guy, which is what I was looking for. So, because I chose an image that I created outside of the character creator, I\'m going to start the'

[02:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'character creation process once again, but this time choose start from an image, and then I\'m going to choose that image that I created. I\'ll then give it a name, Kaylin. And here\'s where it gets really cool. You can now attach a voice to a character so that even that is'

[02:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'consistent every time you use it. To do that, you just click on add a voice, and you can choose from any of the voices here in the 11 Labs library, or in this case, you can create a new voice simply by a prompt by clicking create voice. When you click create new voice,'

[02:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you got a few options. You can upload audio if you\'d like to clone a specific voice, you can record a specific voice, or you can design a voice by just typing a description of what you want that voice to be. I\'m going to give it the prompt a young child with attitude. I'

[02:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t know that the attitude\'s going to be in there, but we can use the young child voice. &gt;&gt; Hi, I\'m your Open Art voice. Use me to bring your character to life. &gt;&gt; So, I like that one. Let\'s add the word alien monster in here and see if we can'

[02:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get something else. &gt;&gt; Hi, I\'m your Open Art voice. Use me to bring your character to life. &gt;&gt; So, I think I\'m going to go back to this'

[03:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one. I\'m going to call this voice Kaylin and click on save voice. And then I just finish up by clicking create. Now, to see what that looks like, we\'re going to come over to the video generator. We\'re going to choose the Seed Dance 2 model, and from the characters, we\'re going to choose our'

[03:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'friend Kaylin. And you can see by this little icon here that the voice is attached. Then we just plug in a prompt, but this is no ordinary prompt. This prompt is written to be the angry version of this character. So, it says he yells in a furious voice, stamping his feet, using'

[03:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'his whole body to communicate his emotion, and pointing at the camera. So, now we get this. &gt;&gt; I\'m Chad, and I\'m reading for the part of Kaylin. &gt;&gt; [clears throat] &gt;&gt; Look, I\'m tired of being treated like I'

[03:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t matter around here. Now, either show me at least a little respect or let me go home. &gt;&gt; So, now this would become video reference for anytime I want to use Kaylin in a scene where he\'s angry. I'

[03:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'created Tracy in the character creator basically the same way except that I used a real image of her rather than an AI generated one. I also created a clone of her voice based on a sample of her real voice. &gt;&gt; I\'m Tracy.'

[04:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Amber here who also auditioned for Jessica, same exact thing except that I used one image which was more of a character sheet that showed her from various angles and again cloned her voice from an actual sample of her voice. &gt;&gt; I\'m Amber. &gt;&gt; The Kevin character who tried out for'

[04:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Cliff exactly the same as Amber except that the voice that I used here was an Eleven Labs voice attached to this character. &gt;&gt; I\'m Daryl. Sorry, I\'m Kevin. I don\'t know why. Sorry, I\'m a little nervous. &gt;&gt; Cindy was also created here in the character creator but we used the build'

[04:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your character option which allows you to choose first their overall look, then their gender, then their ethnicity, their age, and then any other details that you want to type in and that\'s what gave us Cindy. &gt;&gt; I\'m Cindy.'

[04:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Cindy\'s voice was created with the voice designer that I showed you before and at that time I forgot to name it. That\'s why it\'s called voiced and the date I created it. Now you may notice there\'s no Bob character here. That\'s because I used real video of me instead of creating a model. This way I could'

[04:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'capture the nuances that I know I was putting into each of these emotional expressions. &gt;&gt; I don\'t care what you told me. &gt;&gt; And honestly, if you can get it, that\'s what you want. A genuine performance from a real person doing it the way that'

[05:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'only they can do it. So just to recap, there\'s three levels here. If you just use an image reference, you get the look of the person. If you use the reference and the voice, then you have the look and the voice of the person. But if you use an actual video performance of that'

[05:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'person, you\'ve got the voice, the look, and the nuanced performance. And now you know how to build all three versions. Now all of these audition clips and there are a lot, aren\'t just random clips that I generated. In the truest sense of the word, these'

[05:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generations were auditions for which of these versions I was going to use in these production pieces. These videos are the reference video I put into the prompt to make sure that the emotion is expressed. Now of course, if I just use their voice and their picture, I could'

[05:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompt sadness, I could prompt anger, I could prompt fear. But, would it be the exact same performance by that character in every shot I make? There\'s absolutely no guarantee unless you use this method. So, when I need Cliff to be scared, I'

[06:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'use the Cliff scared video reference. &gt;&gt; Oh my god, what the hell was that? &gt;&gt; If I need Jessica to be happy, I use the Jessica happy reference. &gt;&gt; Oh my god, it was crazy. &gt;&gt; So, you\'re truly building a stable of'

[06:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'performances by various actors, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; exactly the right ones for your specific needs. So, here\'s what\'s coming. I\'m going to show you four scenes, four completely different genres, four different emotional registers, and each'

[06:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one uses the specific reference videos needed to make that scene work. Now, before I show you each scene, let me show you the reference videos used for each character\'s emotional state. Now, this is Cindy or Jessica\'s happy video. &gt;&gt; [laughter]'

[06:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; And seriously, you should have seen it. There was cake everywhere. Oh. &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; And this is Bob or Cliff\'s happy video. &gt;&gt; Seriously, you should have seen it. There was cake everywhere. I I Oh my god, it was crazy.'

[06:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Okay. That actually worked. &gt;&gt; I know. &gt;&gt; I genuinely did not think that was going to work. &gt;&gt; I did. &gt;&gt; You also thought the thing before was going to work. &gt;&gt; Different situation. Look, one of them was always going to work. I just needed to find it.'

[07:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; That is not how this is supposed to go. &gt;&gt; And yet, say it. &gt;&gt; were right. &gt;&gt; Louder. &gt;&gt; Absolutely not. &gt;&gt; So, you can see it\'s not like they\'re non-stop laughing throughout the scene. They keep the appropriate tone, but the overall tone of levity and happiness is definitely there. The next clip involves'

[07:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Cindy and Kaylin. Kaylin I kept neutral on this one, but for Cindy, I used this angry reference clip. &gt;&gt; I don\'t care what you told me. It\'s not what you did. And And I\'m just tired of it.'

[07:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; And here\'s the scene. &gt;&gt; Put that down. &gt;&gt; Sorry. &gt;&gt; You told him about the meeting. &gt;&gt; Yes. &gt;&gt; After I asked you not to. &gt;&gt; You asked me not to tell him about the contract. The meeting is different. &gt;&gt; thing. &gt;&gt; They involve the same people, but they are'

[07:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Get out. &gt;&gt; Okay. He took it really well, by the way. &gt;&gt; So, we transferred the tone of her anger and the way she delivers it perfectly, and that is the kind of consistency you really want. For the next clip, we used the sad version of Bob playing the Cliff'

[07:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'character. &gt;&gt; It\'s not what you did. And I am I\'m just tired of it. &gt;&gt; And here is how that emotion was transferred. &gt;&gt; going back to it, the moment I could'

[08:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have changed it. There were a few of those. Yeah, thanks. &gt;&gt; Sorry, I do not always know whether to say the true thing or the helpful thing. &gt;&gt; What\'s the helpful thing? &gt;&gt; That you did your best. &gt;&gt; Did I? &gt;&gt; You did a version of your best. &gt;&gt; That\'s terrible.'

[08:16] [scene:talk]
